efferent \u2192 afferent \u2192 interlobular","Arcuate \u2192 interlobular \u2192 interlobar \u2192 afferent \u2192 efferent","Interlobular \u2192 arcuate \u2192 interlobar \u2192 efferent \u2192 afferent","Arcuate \u2192 interlobar \u2192 interlobular \u2192 efferent \u2192 afferent"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct sequence of arterial blood flow through the kidney is \u003Cstrong\u003Einterlobar \u2192 arcuate \u2192 interlobular \u2192 afferent \u2192 efferent\u003C/strong\u003E. The renal artery enters the kidney and divides into interlobar arteries, which travel between the renal pyramids. These give rise to arcuate arteries that arch along the corticomedullary junction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe arcuate arteries give rise to interlobular arteries that extend into the cortex. These then branch into afferent arterioles that supply the glomeruli. Blood leaves the glomeruli via the efferent arterioles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The afferent arteriole carries blood into the glomerulus while the efferent arteriole transports blood away from the glomerulus.","The interlobular arteries branch from arcuate arteries and give rise to afferent arterioles.","The arcuate arteries run at the junction between the renal cortex and medulla, forming arches between the interlobar arteries."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65233"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18501"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65233"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-16T13:22:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-16T13:22:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11230"}},"content"